{
  "final_answer": "## Annualized Q1 2026 vs. FY2025 Revenue Analysis\n\n### Data (from SpaceX S-1, filed May 20, 2026)\n\n| ($ millions) | Q1 2026 | Q1 2026 Annualized (×4) | FY2025 | Implied Growth |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Consolidated** | 4,694 | **18,776** | 18,674 | **+0.55%** |\n| **Connectivity** | 3,257 | **13,028** | 11,387 | **+14.41%** |\n| Space | 619 | 2,476 | 4,086 | −39.40% |\n| AI | 818 | 3,272 | 3,201 | +2.22% |\n\n### Revenue Concentration\n\n| | Q1 2026 Share | FY2025 Share | Change (pp) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Connectivity | 69.4% | 61.0% | +8.4 |\n| Space | 13.2% | 21.9% | −8.7 |\n| AI | 17.4% | 17.1% | +0.3 |\n\n### Implied Growth Profile and Concentration of Momentum\n\nThe consolidated annualized run-rate of $18,776 million barely exceeds FY2025 ($18,674 million), implying near-zero headline growth of **+0.55%**. However, this flat aggregate figure is the net result of three sharply diverging segment trajectories:\n\n1. **Connectivity is the sole growth engine.** Annualized Connectivity revenue of $13,028 million represents +$1,641 million in incremental annualized revenue over FY2025 — more than *16×* the total consolidated incremental gain of +$102 million. Connectivity's revenue share expanded from 61.0% to 69.4%, and the segment now accounts for over two-thirds of consolidated revenue.\n\n2. **Space is a substantial and offsetting drag.** Annualized Space revenue of $2,476 million is −$1,610 million below FY2025, nearly erasing Connectivity's entire gain. The S-1 cautions that Space revenue is inherently lumpy — Launch Services revenue is recognized at a point in time (upon launch), and the mix of internal versus external launches creates significant period-to-period variability. Q1 may therefore understate full-year Space revenue, but even with that caveat, the quarter's Space run-rate signals material contraction.\n\n3. **AI is essentially flat.** Annualized AI revenue of $3,272 million is only +$71 million above FY2025 (+2.22%). Moreover, the S-1 discloses that Q1 AI advertising revenue was temporarily depressed by an advertising-platform overhaul — suggesting underlying AI growth may be somewhat stronger than the Q1 run-rate indicates.\n\n### What This Says About Concentration of Momentum\n\n**Consolidated momentum is almost entirely concentrated in Connectivity.** The incremental dollar math is stark:\n\n| Segment | Annualized vs. FY2025 Δ ($M) |\n|---|---|\n| Connectivity | +1,641 |\n| Space | −1,610 |\n| AI | +71 |\n| **Consolidated** | **+102** |\n\nConnectivity contributes over 100% of net consolidated growth; Space offsets virtually all of it. Absent Connectivity's expansion, the consolidated business would be contracting at a double-digit rate. This extreme concentration means the consolidated revenue trajectory is overwhelmingly a Connectivity story — a single segment's subscriber and ARPU trends dictate the direction of the entire enterprise. While the S-1's Space-lumpiness caveat suggests Q1 may exaggerate the Space decline, the direction and magnitude of the concentration dynamic are unambiguous: Connectivity is not merely the largest segment but the only segment generating material forward momentum as of early 2026.\n\n### Important Filing Context\n\nAll figures reflect the retrospectively recast consolidated entity under common-control accounting, incorporating xAI (merged February 2, 2026) and X Holdings (merged into xAI March 28, 2025) for all historical periods. No period reflects standalone SpaceX operations exclusively.\n\n{\n  \"sources\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\",\n      \"name\": \"SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026)\"\n    }\n  ]\n}",
